{"type":"message","id":"6c2d89aa","parentId":"3af7e479","timestamp":"2026-04-12T19:25:36.682Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I'm getting clearer:\n\n- Gateway WebSocket is at ws://localhost:3108 (NOT 18789!)\n- But earlier we found Gateway listening at 18789\n- The ws-proxy tries to connect to 3108 but that's wrong - the Gateway is at 18789\n- Port 3102 is the Gateway's WebSocket control plane\n- Port 3103 is the ws-proxy\n- Port 3101 is the context API\n\nBut wait - port 3103 is also the v8 scoring engine. Let me check:```\nLISTEN 0 511 0.0.0.0:3103 node pid=599\n```And the v8 log shows:```\nOpenClaw v8.0 listening on port 3103\n\n\n```\n\nSo there are two things trying to use port 3103 - the ws-proxy service and the v8 scoring engine - but the ws-proxy is the one that's actually bound there. Port 3102 is the Gateway's WebSocket control plane, not the actual message WebSocket. The real Gateway port for messaging appears to be 3108 based on what the ws-proxy is trying to connect to, though 18789 is the main HTTP port for the Gateway.\n\nThe ws-proxy at 3103 connects to 3108 via WebSocket and proxies messages, while 3102 handles the RPC control plane. The v8 system at port 3103 with PID 599 is something else entirely - it's likely the task scoring engine from the openclaw-router setup, not the Python scene-classifier API.\n\n```","thinkingSignature":"14ddd333e00e73b62703876a014d031fd8779c2ee89e64ec16ce49d634f155da"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lyuxegztjy5y_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -v grep | grep \"pid=599\\|pid=432\\|pid=299583\\|pid=299508\" | awk '{print $1, $2, $11, $12, $13, $14, $15, $16, $17}'"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lyuxegztjy5y_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /proc/599/cmdline 2>/dev/null | tr '\\0' ' '; echo; cat /proc/599/environ 2>/dev/null | tr '\\0' '\\n' | grep -E \"PORT\\|HOST\\|NODE\\|HOME\" | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","p