{"type":"message","id":"2dc68c29","parentId":"caeb3b17","timestamp":"2026-04-12T19:26:19.843Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture of the v8 system:\n- v8/src/router/ - routing logic\n- v8/src/scoring/ - scoring engine\n- v8/src/observability/ - health, metrics, logging\n- v8/src/executor/ - task executor\n- v8/src/persistence/ - task store\n- v8/src/security/ - security gateway\n- v8/src/scheduler/ - scheduler\n- v8/src/skills/ - skills\n- v8/src/context/ - context management\n\nThis is a comprehensive task orchestration engine. Let me now understand how the whole system fits together:1. openclaw-router (DEAD) - was supposed to be the HTTP/WS proxy and router between Gateway and v8\n\n\n2. ws-proxy (DEAD) - was supposed to forward WebSocket traffic to Gateway\n3. context-api (RUNNING, PID 432) - a simple message context store\n4. v8 scoring engine (RUNNING, PID 599) - at port 3103\n5. Scene Classifier (RUNNING, PID 299508) - Python FastAPI at port 3104\n\nBut there's a critical mismatch: the router and ws-proxy are both trying to reach the Gateway WebSocket at port 3108, but nothing is actually listening there. The actual Gateway is running at different ports, so all these connections are failing.\n\nThe whole setup appears to be a complex HTTP/WebSocket proxy and routing layer that was supposed to sit in front of the OpenClaw Gateway, with each component getting restart commands from systemd but immediately failing because they can't reach their targets. Plus there's a v8 scoring engine running at 3103 that appears to be disconnected from everything else, and a separate Python Scene Classifier service at 3104 that might be the real intent classification system being used instead.","thinkingSignature":"8cf01364775c62bd0e69f37751829b2998349730a4f935a3b172b38af036bd0d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_brfqg367nc0f_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3104/classi